{"id":1245802813,"created_at":"2022-05-23T23:33:21Z","updated_at":"2022-05-23T23:33:21Z","state":"open","title":"check into using SWT instead of AWT/Swing","html_url":"https://github.com/crowlogic/arb4j/issues/34","body":"https://www.eclipse.org/swt/opengl/"}
{"id":772898511,"created_at":"2020-12-22T12:09:50Z","updated_at":"2022-04-11T13:24:49Z","state":"open","title":"AWT & Swing on Windows","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/graal/issues/3084","body":"AWT & Swing are not currently supported on Windows. There are several aspects to adding this support, so the aim of this issue is to describe the overall approach. The actual work will be done under separate issues.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Linking with Native Libraries\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to linking, we considered both options: static and dynamic. However, initial testing (which was fairly basic) has already revealed problems with static linking that can't be reasonably solved without modifying the JDK (e.g., it affects the [static initialization order](https://isocpp.org/wiki/faq/ctors#static-init-order) in such a way as to cause a segfault). On the other hand, dynamic linking allows us to reuse native libraries as they are.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the plan is to add support for dynamic linking, as there are fewer unknowns.\r\n\r\nWork is currently in progress: #3085\r\n\r\n\r\n### Swing\r\n\r\nNative images currently have `java.home` set to `null`. This is problematic as the Swing code assumes the existence and layout of the `java.home` directory in order to load various configurations. So to avoid Swing substitutions, we need a real directory with the expected layout and content.\r\n\r\nThe plan is to set `java.home` to the directory from which the native image is executed.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Build Output\r\n\r\nBoth dynamic linking and Swing support imply that the output of a native image build will no longer be a single binary, but multiple binaries or even a whole directory.\r\n\r\nThe current plan is to put everything next to the built native image, which should be enough to enable proper functioning. Later, we could introduce some configurability and / or support to bundle everything into a zip archive.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Build Configuration\r\n\r\nCurrently, the use of `native-image-agent` ([see documentation](https://github.com/oracle/graal/blob/master/substratevm/BuildConfiguration.md#assisted-configuration-of-native-image-builds)) is required even in the most trivial cases. And while this should be possible to improve, at this point it is difficult to say to what extent.\r\n\r\nThe rough idea is to provide AWT & Swing configurations out of the box where possible.\r\n"}
{"id":1218624115,"created_at":"2022-04-28T11:59:45Z","updated_at":"2022-05-28T09:35:16Z","state":"open","title":"8213531: Test javax/swing/border/TestTitledBorderLeak.java fails","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8450","body":"Test was failing in linux citing `java.lang.RuntimeException: Expected Total TitledBorder to be freed : 10 Freed 9 `\r\nAs per the fix done in JDK-8204963 http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk/jdk/rev/cd7d2f9154fd\r\nthere was no platform specific code done for the fix and logs in `TitledBorder.installPropertyChangeListeners` shows it was called 10 times for the test but `CleanerFactory.cleaner().register` action was only called 9 times in linux causing it to fail.\r\n\r\nModified the test to not show the frame which cause the problem to go away and also it can still be used as 8204963 regression test as it still fails without the fix and pass with it. {"id":1229511548,"created_at":"2022-05-09T10:37:53Z","updated_at":"2022-05-11T13:59:28Z","state":"open","title":"Use kotlinx-coroutines for UI launcher","html_url":"https://github.com/apache/jmeter/pull/712","body":"## Description\r\n\r\nThis PR moves `startGui` from `class JMeter` to another class.\r\n\r\n## Motivation and Context\r\n\r\na) It is nice to factor UI from non-UI code\r\nb) Current code fails to update progress during \"GUI startup\". The reason is that all the contents of `startGui` is running in a single `Runnable`, so Swing has no way to break in-between and render progress updates.\r\nSee https://bz.apache.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=66044#c5\r\n\r\nCoroutines enable an easy-to-maintain approach for splitting long UI methods into chunks.\r\nIn this case, I used `yield()` right after `setProgress`, so we give room for the Swing event dispatcher thread to update the UI.\r\n\r\nSee also https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx.coroutines/blob/master/ui/coroutines-guide-ui.md\r\n\r\n## Checklist:\r\n<!--- Go over all the following points, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->\r\n<!--- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask. We're here to help! -->\r\n- [x] My code follows the [code style][style-guide] of this project.\r\n- [ ] I have updated the documentation accordingly.\r\n\r\n[style-guide]: https://wiki.apache.org/jmeter/CodeStyleGuidelines\r\n"}
{"id":979080380,"created_at":"2021-08-25T12:20:36Z","updated_at":"2021-11-06T02:17:38Z","state":"open","title":"WIP: Swing chat","html_url":"https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/pull/3104","body":"This converts the custom board view overlay from to use Swing components, removing the two duplicate chat UI implementations and a lot of custom widget-like code.\r\n\r\nThis is a WIP since there's a JTextComponent issue causing repaint issues when animating the text areas, I'm still looking into it but suggestions welcome. :)\r\n\r\nA few new utility classes are included. The input redirector is maybe only specific to this chat UI, but the animator and HUD classes I'm interested in using elsewhere - for animating sidebar panels for unit details and the round report open and closed, and moving status into the main window as an overlay."}

{"id":1221787757,"created_at":"2022-04-30T09:33:38Z","updated_at":"2022-05-28T12:23:18Z","state":"open","title":"[PATCH] Avoid redundant HashMap.containsKey calls in NimbusDefaults","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8482","body":"The method `javax.swing.plaf.nimbus.NimbusDefaults#getDerivedColor(String,String,float,float,float,int,boolean)` could be improved by usage of Map.putIfAbsent instead of separate `containsKey`/`get`/`put` calls. We known that HashMap `javax.swing.plaf.nimbus.NimbusDefaults#derivedColors` can contain only non-null values. And to check if `putIfAbsent` was successful or not, we can just compare result with `null`.\r\nIt makes code a bit cleaner and faster.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [ ] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [ ] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8482/head:pull/8482` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8482`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8482` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8482/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8482`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8482`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8482.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8482.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":185754093,"created_at":"2016-10-27T19:06:56Z","updated_at":"2016-10-27T19:06:56Z","state":"open","title":"Test Swing?","html_url":"https://github.com/navpil/coinage/issues/32","body":"How to test Swing application? Are there some build-in tools or some framework? Is there a simple way?\n"}
{"id":1191115550,"created_at":"2022-04-04T01:05:53Z","updated_at":"2022-04-08T21:22:36Z","state":"open","title":"OptionsLookAndFeel: Support for FlatLaf","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/pull/65","body":"@ctrueden, this PR is a proposal on how [Flatlaf](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf#flatlaf---flat-look-and-feel) could be used as an _optional_ L&F for Swing components in Fiji/SciJava in direct response to #61. The advantages of FlatLaf L&Fs are discussed in #61, and  include:\r\n- Proper hiDPI scaling under Java 8 (this is mainly relevant to linux nowadays, but still relevant to other OSes: e.g., Native L&F on the mac scales everything without judgment, and so margins and borders become awkwardly exaggerated: this does not happen with FlatFlaf)\r\n- Much more modern and polished 'feel' relative to JVM default options\r\n- Several fixes for current Swing bugs and limitations that will not be fixed upstream\r\n- Many improvements like[ improved submenu navigation](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/releases/tag/2.1)\r\n- Dark themes, that have been asked several times, e.g., in the script editor [here](https://forum.image.sc/t/shiny-new-script-editor/64160/37?u=tferr), and [here](https://github.com/scijava/script-editor/pull/56#issuecomment-1050888837)\r\n\r\nThis PR also includes a  static method so that Look and Feel can be set more easily at startup. E.g., for Fjii the following\r\ncall in the StartupMacros could now be used to set the Look and Feel programmatically:\r\n```\r\neval(\"js\",\"importClass(Packages.org.scijava.ui.swing.options.OptionsLookAndFeel);OptionsLookAndFeel.setupLookAndFeel('FlatLaf Dark');\") \r\n```\r\nA couple of notes:\r\n- The flatlaf dependency is now being declared in this pom. I assume it should be declared in the parent pom-scijava? I imagine multiple releases of components would be needed, so if you don't mind I would pass that work onto you\r\n- If this gets merged, dark themes in Fiji would still remain problematic. In addition to the obvious fact that  java.awt components will not change, there are currently some hardwired colors in several components (e.g., Console) that would need to be patched for dark themes to work properly. One would need to remove/adjust explicit `setColor()` references in the code. I am not doing that here, in case there are technical issues with adopting third-party L&F libraries that I am not foreseeing, and this cannot be merged.\r\n- I would actually vote for FlatLaf to be the default in Fiji (for the reasons above). However, on the Mac AWT and Swing are too intertwined, and currently choosing a flatlaf theme on MacOS, makes some components of the GenericDialog loose rounded edges. So it may be wise for the time being to consider the possibility of having it as a default only on Windows and Linux. I will open an issue there to see if this can be fixed."}

{"id":1048430859,"created_at":"2021-11-09T10:21:40Z","updated_at":"2021-11-09T10:21:40Z","state":"open","title":"Made StatusBar swing timer stoppable","html_url":"https://github.com/NASAWorldWind/WorldWindJava/pull/234","body":"### Description of the Change\r\n\r\nIn the class gov.nasa.worldwind.util.StatusBar a SwingTimer is created as a local variable in the constructor. This way the timer can never be stopped.\r\n\r\n### Why Should This Be In Core?\r\n\r\nEvery Application which does not rely on System.exit() for its shutdown could have a problem with the timer mentioned above as the AWT Thread won't stop. Usage of System.exit() can be a problem if there are automated system tests executed by tools like the maven-failsafe-plugin, which does not allow for such calls.\r\n\r\n### Benefits\r\n\r\nThe timer can be stopped and applications can do a graceful shutdown.\r\n\r\n### Potential Drawbacks\r\n\r\nThere is the risk that a programmer calls the stop method and wonders why the network status is not updated anymore. It could even be argued that the encapsulation is broken but by using global state like the swing timer facility there is no other practical way to clean this up the way it is currently designed.\r\n\r\n### Applicable Issues"}

{"id":1245802813,"created_at":"2022-05-23T23:33:21Z","updated_at":"2022-05-23T23:33:21Z","state":"open","title":"check into using SWT instead of AWT/Swing","html_url":"https://github.com/crowlogic/arb4j/issues/34","body":"https://www.eclipse.org/swt/opengl/"}
{"id":772898511,"created_at":"2020-12-22T12:09:50Z","updated_at":"2022-04-11T13:24:49Z","state":"open","title":"AWT & Swing on Windows","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/graal/issues/3084","body":"AWT & Swing are not currently supported on Windows. There are several aspects to adding this support, so the aim of this issue is to describe the overall approach. The actual work will be done under separate issues.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Linking with Native Libraries\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to linking, we considered both options: static and dynamic. However, initial testing (which was fairly basic) has already revealed problems with static linking that can't be reasonably solved without modifying the JDK (e.g., it affects the [static initialization order](https://isocpp.org/wiki/faq/ctors#static-init-order) in such a way as to cause a segfault). On the other hand, dynamic linking allows us to reuse native libraries as they are.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the plan is to add support for dynamic linking, as there are fewer unknowns.\r\n\r\nWork is currently in progress: #3085\r\n\r\n\r\n### Swing\r\n\r\nNative images currently have `java.home` set to `null`. This is problematic as the Swing code assumes the existence and layout of the `java.home` directory in order to load various configurations. So to avoid Swing substitutions, we need a real directory with the expected layout and content.\r\n\r\nThe plan is to set `java.home` to the directory from which the native image is executed.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Build Output\r\n\r\nBoth dynamic linking and Swing support imply that the output of a native image build will no longer be a single binary, but multiple binaries or even a whole directory.\r\n\r\nThe current plan is to put everything next to the built native image, which should be enough to enable proper functioning. Later, we could introduce some configurability and / or support to bundle everything into a zip archive.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Build Configuration\r\n\r\nCurrently, the use of `native-image-agent` ([see documentation](https://github.com/oracle/graal/blob/master/substratevm/BuildConfiguration.md#assisted-configuration-of-native-image-builds)) is required even in the most trivial cases. And while this should be possible to improve, at this point it is difficult to say to what extent.\r\n\r\nThe rough idea is to provide AWT & Swing configurations out of the box where possible.\r\n"}
{"id":1218624115,"created_at":"2022-04-28T11:59:45Z","updated_at":"2022-05-28T09:35:16Z","state":"open","title":"8213531: Test javax/swing/border/TestTitledBorderLeak.java fails","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8450","body":"Test was failing in linux citing `java.lang.RuntimeException: Expected Total TitledBorder to be freed : 10 Freed 9 `\r\nAs per the fix done in JDK-8204963 http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk/jdk/rev/cd7d2f9154fd\r\nthere was no platform specific code done for the fix and logs in `TitledBorder.installPropertyChangeListeners` shows it was called 10 times for the test but `CleanerFactory.cleaner().register` action was only called 9 times in linux causing it to fail.\r\n\r\nModified the test to not show the frame which cause the problem to go away and also it can still be used as 8204963 regression test as it still fails without the fix and pass with it. {"id":1229511548,"created_at":"2022-05-09T10:37:53Z","updated_at":"2022-05-11T13:59:28Z","state":"open","title":"Use kotlinx-coroutines for UI launcher","html_url":"https://github.com/apache/jmeter/pull/712","body":"## Description\r\n\r\nThis PR moves `startGui` from `class JMeter` to another class.\r\n\r\n## Motivation and Context\r\n\r\na) It is nice to factor UI from non-UI code\r\nb) Current code fails to update progress during \"GUI startup\". The reason is that all the contents of `startGui` is running in a single `Runnable`, so Swing has no way to break in-between and render progress updates.\r\nSee https://bz.apache.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=66044#c5\r\n\r\nCoroutines enable an easy-to-maintain approach for splitting long UI methods into chunks.\r\nIn this case, I used `yield()` right after `setProgress`, so we give room for the Swing event dispatcher thread to update the UI.\r\n\r\nSee also https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx.coroutines/blob/master/ui/coroutines-guide-ui.md\r\n\r\n## Checklist:\r\n<!--- Go over all the following points, and put an `x` in all the boxes that apply. -->\r\n<!--- If you're unsure about any of these, don't hesitate to ask. We're here to help! -->\r\n- [x] My code follows the [code style][style-guide] of this project.\r\n- [ ] I have updated the documentation accordingly.\r\n\r\n[style-guide]: https://wiki.apache.org/jmeter/CodeStyleGuidelines\r\n"}
{"id":979080380,"created_at":"2021-08-25T12:20:36Z","updated_at":"2021-11-06T02:17:38Z","state":"open","title":"WIP: Swing chat","html_url":"https://github.com/MegaMek/megamek/pull/3104","body":"This converts the custom board view overlay from to use Swing components, removing the two duplicate chat UI implementations and a lot of custom widget-like code.\r\n\r\nThis is a WIP since there's a JTextComponent issue causing repaint issues when animating the text areas, I'm still looking into it but suggestions welcome. :)\r\n\r\nA few new utility classes are included. The input redirector is maybe only specific to this chat UI, but the animator and HUD classes I'm interested in using elsewhere - for animating sidebar panels for unit details and the round report open and closed, and moving status into the main window as an overlay."}

{"id":1221787757,"created_at":"2022-04-30T09:33:38Z","updated_at":"2022-05-28T12:23:18Z","state":"open","title":"[PATCH] Avoid redundant HashMap.containsKey calls in NimbusDefaults","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8482","body":"The method `javax.swing.plaf.nimbus.NimbusDefaults#getDerivedColor(String,String,float,float,float,int,boolean)` could be improved by usage of Map.putIfAbsent instead of separate `containsKey`/`get`/`put` calls. We known that HashMap `javax.swing.plaf.nimbus.NimbusDefaults#derivedColors` can contain only non-null values. And to check if `putIfAbsent` was successful or not, we can just compare result with `null`.\r\nIt makes code a bit cleaner and faster.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [ ] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [ ] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8482/head:pull/8482` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8482`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8482` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8482/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8482`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8482`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8482.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8482.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":185754093,"created_at":"2016-10-27T19:06:56Z","updated_at":"2016-10-27T19:06:56Z","state":"open","title":"Test Swing?","html_url":"https://github.com/navpil/coinage/issues/32","body":"How to test Swing application? Are there some build-in tools or some framework? Is there a simple way?\n"}
{"id":1191115550,"created_at":"2022-04-04T01:05:53Z","updated_at":"2022-04-08T21:22:36Z","state":"open","title":"OptionsLookAndFeel: Support for FlatLaf","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/pull/65","body":"@ctrueden, this PR is a proposal on how [Flatlaf](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf#flatlaf---flat-look-and-feel) could be used as an _optional_ L&F for Swing components in Fiji/SciJava in direct response to #61. The advantages of FlatLaf L&Fs are discussed in #61, and  include:\r\n- Proper hiDPI scaling under Java 8 (this is mainly relevant to linux nowadays, but still relevant to other OSes: e.g., Native L&F on the mac scales everything without judgment, and so margins and borders become awkwardly exaggerated: this does not happen with FlatFlaf)\r\n- Much more modern and polished 'feel' relative to JVM default options\r\n- Several fixes for current Swing bugs and limitations that will not be fixed upstream\r\n- Many improvements like[ improved submenu navigation](https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf/releases/tag/2.1)\r\n- Dark themes, that have been asked several times, e.g., in the script editor [here](https://forum.image.sc/t/shiny-new-script-editor/64160/37?u=tferr), and [here](https://github.com/scijava/script-editor/pull/56#issuecomment-1050888837)\r\n\r\nThis PR also includes a  static method so that Look and Feel can be set more easily at startup. E.g., for Fjii the following\r\ncall in the StartupMacros could now be used to set the Look and Feel programmatically:\r\n```\r\neval(\"js\",\"importClass(Packages.org.scijava.ui.swing.options.OptionsLookAndFeel);OptionsLookAndFeel.setupLookAndFeel('FlatLaf Dark');\") \r\n```\r\nA couple of notes:\r\n- The flatlaf dependency is now being declared in this pom. I assume it should be declared in the parent pom-scijava? I imagine multiple releases of components would be needed, so if you don't mind I would pass that work onto you\r\n- If this gets merged, dark themes in Fiji would still remain problematic. In addition to the obvious fact that  java.awt components will not change, there are currently some hardwired colors in several components (e.g., Console) that would need to be patched for dark themes to work properly. One would need to remove/adjust explicit `setColor()` references in the code. I am not doing that here, in case there are technical issues with adopting third-party L&F libraries that I am not foreseeing, and this cannot be merged.\r\n- I would actually vote for FlatLaf to be the default in Fiji (for the reasons above). However, on the Mac AWT and Swing are too intertwined, and currently choosing a flatlaf theme on MacOS, makes some components of the GenericDialog loose rounded edges. So it may be wise for the time being to consider the possibility of having it as a default only on Windows and Linux. I will open an issue there to see if this can be fixed."}

{"id":1048430859,"created_at":"2021-11-09T10:21:40Z","updated_at":"2021-11-09T10:21:40Z","state":"open","title":"Made StatusBar swing timer stoppable","html_url":"https://github.com/NASAWorldWind/WorldWindJava/pull/234","body":"### Description of the Change\r\n\r\nIn the class gov.nasa.worldwind.util.StatusBar a SwingTimer is created as a local variable in the constructor. This way the timer can never be stopped.\r\n\r\n### Why Should This Be In Core?\r\n\r\nEvery Application which does not rely on System.exit() for its shutdown could have a problem with the timer mentioned above as the AWT Thread won't stop. Usage of System.exit() can be a problem if there are automated system tests executed by tools like the maven-failsafe-plugin, which does not allow for such calls.\r\n\r\n### Benefits\r\n\r\nThe timer can be stopped and applications can do a graceful shutdown.\r\n\r\n### Potential Drawbacks\r\n\r\nThere is the risk that a programmer calls the stop method and wonders why the network status is not updated anymore. It could even be argued that the encapsulation is broken but by using global state like the swing timer facility there is no other practical way to clean this up the way it is currently designed.\r\n\r\n### Applicable Issues"}

{"id":585968873,"created_at":"2020-03-23T06:38:27Z","updated_at":"2020-03-23T11:09:41Z","state":"open","title":"Commentpane to swing component","html_url":"https://github.com/featurecat/lizzie/pull/696","body":"I was bored yesterday and I was going through issues in Lizzie and I saw that wordwrap was requested for the comment pane in issue #676 \r\n\r\nI jumped into the code and realised that all components are converted into graphics and then those are stitched together for the UI.\r\n\r\nAs a thought exercise I extracted the comment pane into a separate component, JTextArea. I also had to extract the tree but I still left that as a graphics component.\r\n\r\nIt could be a step forward to having Java components rather than just graphics.\r\n\r\nAnother big change in this pull request is I'm skipping a lot of repaints for Leelaz. I saw that the UI sluggish because painting was happening very often when the engine is providing all kind of info. As most of the info you can ignore (it does not matter if the scores change 10 times a second or 2 times) then I'm skipping repaints unless there 700ms has passed since the previous one.\r\n\r\nI realise that this is not the best pull request as it is based on my working tree that has other fixes in \r\nit but I'm still submitting this as the component conversion can be taken separately if there is interest.\r\n\r\nThe same goes for the UI changes."}
{"id":543716007,"created_at":"2019-12-30T03:56:39Z","updated_at":"2021-09-15T13:45:03Z","state":"open","title":"Feature/#2908 swing ui improvements","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/pull/2911","body":"Fixes #2908 \r\nFixes #2836 \r\nFixes #2825 \r\nFixes #2469 \r\nFixes #1880\r\n\r\nThis is a large change to the structure of the Swing interface so I've created a feature branch for it so it can be tested a bit more extensively.  The ZK interface has not been affected.\r\n\r\nFeature wise, it changes the look and feel of the swing editors, making them act consistently in forms and the table.  The table can freeze columns similar to a spreadsheet.  When a field has the focus, in the form or table, typing will start editing the field.  The Enter key will stop editing and commit the change.  The Escape key will revert the change to the field.  The tab key will stop editing, commit the change and move to the next field.\r\n\r\nIn a form, when not editing a field, the Enter key will act on the button that has the focus or the default button if no button has the focus.  In the table, the Enter key or shift Enter will move the focus\r\nup and down.  Tab will cycle the focus to the right. Shift tab will cycle to the left.  The Home and End key will move the focus to the first or last cell in the row.\r\n\r\nIn the form, F2 will create a new record but in the table F2 will start editing a field.  To create a new record in the table, click Ctrl-F2.\r\n\r\nThe combo box has been changed to use a more flexible form of auto-completion and auto-reduction.  The popup will appear and show entries that have a partial match to the typed text.  For example \"li\" will match Eng**li**sh and Ita**li**ano.  Typing Enter will select the highlighted choice.  Enter again will commit the change.\r\n\r\nEscaping or ignoring a change with the Escape key will first revert the change to the field being edited and stop the editor.  If no field is being edited, the Escape key will revert the changes to any other field since the last commit of the record.  This helps when entering data where a mistake is made.  Previously, the Escape key would wipe the entire record, deleting all the other fields as well.  Now, the user can just revert the one field with one click of Escape or the entire record with two clicks of Escape.\r\n\r\nThe delete key will delete the contents of the field that has the focus.\r\n\r\nThe Date field will show a light grey hint when it has the focus as an editor and a null value.  The hint will use the date format applied.\r\n\r\nIn the table, right clicking in the header will show a pop-up that can be used to hide columns or freeze columns.  If Freeze is selected, all the columns to the left will be frozen in place.  Sizing of the frozen columns in not possible but the rest of the table can be manipulated as required.  The focus moves seamlessly between the frozen columns and the main table.  Right click in the header again to unfreeze the columns.\r\n\r\nThe way columns are hidden has been changed so that the columns are removed from the table view model.  This allows focus to move cleanly around that table.  Previously, the hidden columns existed in the view but were not shown, resulting in the focus disapearing when a hidden columns was selected.\r\n\r\nThe cell renderers and cell editors use the same representation as the form.  The method of testing the context for dynamic display uses the table or context as required to provide the same functionality whether in the form or table.\r\n\r\nIn separating the Swing interface from the Base classes, there are several cases where public methods that returned swing classes have been moved to the Client.  Where possible I deprecated these changes but it wasn't possible in all cases.\r\n\r\nThe Swing PLAF files have been moved to the Client and I've added UI elements for most of the editors.  This speeds up their creation a fair bit as all the UI setup was being done twice.  The way the editor are displayed is more consistent and appear similar to the ComboBox.  Behind the scenes an abstract editor now contains most of the editor code and an abstract UI element handles most of the common UI appearance.  This has reduced the complexity and amount of duplicated code  quite a bit.\r\n\r\nI really enjoy using the new interface compared to the previous one and I hope you do as well.\r\n"}

{"id":1175734104,"created_at":"2022-03-21T17:47:28Z","updated_at":"2022-03-21T18:46:53Z","state":"open","title":"4.3.0 Callgraph edges dropped in javax.swing.JComponent (?)","html_url":"https://github.com/soot-oss/soot/issues/1846","body":"**Description, Input**\r\n\r\nWe use soot's spark callgraph generation with the following options:\r\n\r\n```java\r\nOptions.v().set_verbose(false);\r\nOptions.v().set_whole_program(true);\r\nOptions.v().set_app(true);\r\nOptions.v().set_allow_phantom_refs(true);\r\nOptions.v().set_output_format(Options.output_format_class);\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"jb\", \"use-original-names:true\");\r\nOptions.v().set_include_all(true);\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"cg\", \"types-for-invoke:true\");\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"cg.cha\", \"enabled:false\");\r\n// Enable SPARK\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"cg.spark\", \"enabled:true\");\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"cg.spark\", \"verbose:true\");\r\nOptions.v().setPhaseOption(\"cg.spark\", \"on-fly-cg:true\");\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe following test application, when analyzed using soot 4.2.1, provides a callgraph which extends back through to the `actionPerformed` methods in the `ActionListener`s:\r\n\r\n```java\r\nimport javax.swing.JFrame;\r\nimport javax.swing.JButton;\r\nimport java.awt.event.ActionEvent;\r\nimport java.awt.event.ActionListener;\r\n\r\n\r\npublic class TinyUI\r\n{\r\n    public class Printer implements ActionListener\r\n    {\r\n        public void actionPerformed( final ActionEvent e )\r\n        {\r\n            System.out.println(\"printing\");\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public class Quitter implements ActionListener\r\n    {\r\n        public void actionPerformed( final ActionEvent e )\r\n        {\r\n            System.exit(0);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public static void main( final String[] args )\r\n    {\r\n        final JFrame frame = new JFrame();\r\n        frame.setSize( 400, 500 );\r\n        frame.setLayout( null );\r\n        frame.setVisible( true );\r\n\r\n        final JButton printButton = new JButton( \"print\" );\r\n        printButton.addActionListener( new TinyUI().new Printer() );\r\n        printButton.setBounds( 10, 10, 100, 100 );\r\n        frame.add( printButton );\r\n\r\n        final JButton quitButton = new JButton( \"quit\" );\r\n        quitButton.addActionListener( new TinyUI().new Quitter() );\r\n        quitButton.setBounds( 10, 200, 100, 100 );\r\n        frame.add( quitButton );\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    private static void DebloatThisFunction() {}\r\n}\r\n```\r\nUsing soot 4.3.0, the callgraph does not extend to the `ActionListener`s, e.g. `TinyUI$Printer: void actionPerformed(java.awt.event.ActionEvent)`.\r\n\r\n**Reproduction**\r\nWe examine the callgraph with the following code:\r\n```java\r\nCallGraph cg = Scene.v().getCallGraph();\r\n```\r\n**Expected**\r\nFrom a high level the \"correct\" callgraph should, at least, include a connection back to these `actionPerformed` methods.  I have done a relatively extensive tracing through the 4.2.1 and 4.3.0 callgraphs and, due to the complexity of these swing event handlers, it's a little unclear what _correct_ would actually look like.  In essence, the major problem is that there is no connection between the backend framework and this test code in 4.3.0.\r\n\r\n**Stacktrace**\r\nWhile there is no stacktrace, these are notes that I've collected while trying to debug this:\r\n* Soot output:\r\n    `[ERROR] Failed Typing in <java.awt.image.ComponentColorModel: int getRGBComponent(int,int)> at statement l3#1 = $r0: Is not cast compatible: null_type <-- java.lang.Object`\r\n* 4.3.0 does not have a `doClick()` in the callgraph. (exists in 4.2.1)\r\n* Adding a programmatic `doClick()` in `main()` generates a callgraph connection to both `actionPerformed` methods. \r\n* 4.3.0 callgraph does not contain `getColorModel` which should be a JButton method.  (exists in 4.2.1)\r\n* It's possible that the methods \"after\" `getColorModel` are not properly processed when generating the callgraph.\r\n* The EventListener framework appears to be dropped from the callgraph in 4.3.0.\r\n\r\n**Additional context**\r\nWe would like to help continue debugging this issue so any advice would be appreciated.  My current theory is that the processing of JComponent fails, potentially where the typing failure happens, and additional critical methods are \"dropped\" from the scene.\r\n\r\nI will post a followup code sample that isolates the `not cast compatible: null_type` error."}

java.awt.event.ActionEvent;\r\nimport java.awt.event.ActionListener;\r\nimport java.awt.event.MouseAdapter;\r\nimport java.awt.event.MouseEvent;\r\nimport java.awt.event.MouseListener;\r\nimport java.awt.event.WindowAdapter;\r\nimport java.awt.event.WindowEvent;\r\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\r\nimport java.util.HashMap;\r\nimport java.util.List;\r\nimport java.util.Map;\r\n\r\nimport javax.swing.BorderFactory;\r\nimport javax.swing.Icon;\r\nimport javax.swing.ImageIcon;\r\nimport javax.swing.JButton;\r\nimport javax.swing.JCheckBox;\r\nimport javax.swing.JComboBox;\r\nimport javax.swing.JComponent;\r\nimport javax.swing.JDialog;\r\nimport javax.swing.JLabel;\r\nimport javax.swing.JPanel;\r\nimport javax.swing.JScrollPane;\r\nimport javax.swing.SwingWorker;\r\nimport javax.swing.border.Border;\r\nimport javax.swing.border.EtchedBorder;\r\n\r\nimport jiconfont.IconCode;\r\nimport jiconfont.IconFont;\r\nimport jiconfont.bundle.Bundle;\r\nimport jiconfont.swing.IconFontSwing;\r\n\r\npublic class IconCodeDialog extends JDialog {\r\n\r\n  private Map<String, IconCollection> icons = new HashMap<>();\r\n  private JPanel grid;\r\n  private int size = 24;\r\n\r\n  private JComboBox iconsComboBox;\r\n  private JComboBox<Integer> sizeComboBox;\r\n  private JCheckBox showNames = new JCheckBox();\r\n  \r\n  private Border iconBorder = BorderFactory.createEtchedBorder(EtchedBorder.LOWERED);\r\n  \r\n  private IconCode selectedIcon;\r\n  private MouseListener onSelectIconMouse;\r\n  private JScrollPane scrollPane;\r\n  \r\n\r\n  public IconCodeDialog() {\r\n    setTitle(\"Icons\");\r\n    setModal(true);\r\n    setLayout(new BorderLayout());\r\n    setPreferredSize(new Dimension(500, 500));\r\n\r\n    for (IconFont iconFont : Bundle.getIconFonts()) {\r\n      IconFontSwing.register(iconFont);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    for (IconCode icon : Bundle.getIcons()) {\r\n      register(icon);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    initComponents();\r\n    updateIcons();\r\n    pack();\r\n    \r\n\r\n  }\r\n \r\n  public IconCode getSelectedIcon() {\r\n    return selectedIcon;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  private void updateIcons() {\r\n    \r\n    Object selectedItem = iconsComboBox.getSelectedItem();\r\n    load(grid, icons.get(selectedItem));\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  public void load(final JPanel panel, IconCollection iconCollection) {\r\n\r\n    final boolean showNamesOpt = showNames.isSelected();\r\n    SwingWorker<Boolean, JComponent> sw1 = new SwingWorker<Boolean, JComponent>() {\r\n\r\n      @Override\r\n      protected Boolean doInBackground() throws Exception {\r\n        \r\n        grid.removeAll();\r\n\r\n        for (final IconCode icon : iconCollection.getIcons()) {\r\n          JLabel label = new JLabel();\r\n          label.setIcon(IconFontSwing.buildIcon(icon, size, Color.BLACK));\r\n          label.putClientProperty(\"IconCode\", icon);\r\n          label.addMouseListener(onSelectIconMouse);\r\n          label.setToolTipText(icon.toString()); \r\n          \r\n          if(showNamesOpt) {\r\n            label.setText(icon.toString());\r\n            label.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(120, size +10));\r\n          }else {\r\n            label.setHorizontalAlignment(JLabel.CENTER);\r\n            label.setVerticalAlignment(JLabel.CENTER);\r\n            label.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(size+10, size+10));\r\n          }\r\n          \r\n//          label.setHorizontalTextPosition(JLabel.CENTER);\r\n//          label.setVerticalTextPosition(JLabel.BOTTOM);\r\n          \r\n          label.setCursor(Cursor.getPredefinedCursor(Cursor.HAND_CURSOR));\r\n          label.setBorder(iconBorder);\r\n          \r\n          publish(label);\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        return true;\r\n      }\r\n\r\n      @Override\r\n      protected void process(List<JComponent> chunks) {\r\n        for (Object object : chunks) {\r\n          panel.add((JComponent) object);\r\n        }\r\n      }\r\n\r\n      @Override\r\n      protected void done() {\r\n        scrollPane.revalidate();\r\n      }\r\n    };\r\n\r\n    // executes the swingworker on worker thread\r\n    sw1.execute();\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  private void initComponents() {\r\n\r\n    JPanel topPanel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());\r\n    iconsComboBox = new JComboBox<Object>(icons.keySet().toArray());\r\n    sizeComboBox = new JComboBox<Integer>(new Integer[] {24, 30, 45, 50});\r\n    \r\n    iconsComboBox.setSelectedIndex(0);\r\n    sizeComboBox.setSelectedIndex(0);\r\n    \r\n    showNames.setText(\"Show Names\");\r\n    showNames.setSelected(false);\r\n    \r\n    topPanel.add(iconsComboBox);\r\n    topPanel.add(showNames);\r\n    topPanel.add(sizeComboBox);\r\n\r\n    JPanel butons = new JPanel(new FlowLayout());\r\n    butons.add(new JButton(\"OK\"));\r\n\r\n    grid = new JPanel();\r\n    grid.setLayout(new GridLayout(0, 11));\r\n    \r\n    scrollPane = new JScrollPane(grid);\r\n    scrollPane.setHorizontalScrollBarPolicy(JScrollPane.HORIZONTAL_SCROLLBAR_AS_NEEDED);\r\n    scrollPane.setVerticalScrollBarPolicy(JScrollPane.VERTICAL_SCROLLBAR_ALWAYS);\r\n    scrollPane.getVerticalScrollBar().setUnitIncrement(20);\r\n//    scrollPane.setSize(new Dimension(800, 600));\r\n    \r\n    \r\n\r\n    add(topPanel, BorderLayout.NORTH);\r\n    add(scrollPane, BorderLayout.CENTER);\r\n    add(butons, BorderLayout.SOUTH);\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    ActionListener updateIconsAction = new ActionListener() {\r\n      @Override\r\n      public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {\r\n        size = (int) sizeComboBox.getSelectedItem();\r\n        updateIcons();\r\n      }\r\n    };\r\n\r\n    iconsComboBox.addActionListener(updateIconsAction);\r\n    showNames.addActionListener(updateIconsAction);\r\n    sizeComboBox.addActionListener(updateIconsAction);\r\n    \r\n    onSelectIconMouse = new MouseAdapter() {\r\n      @Override\r\n      public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {\r\n        JComponent component = (JComponent) e.getSource();\r\n        selectedIcon = (IconCode) component.getClientProperty(\"IconCode\");\r\n        dispose();\r\n      }\r\n    };\r\n\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  public void register(IconCode icon) {\r\n    IconCollection iconCollection = icons.get(icon.getFontFamily());\r\n    if (iconCollection == null) {\r\n      iconCollection = new IconCollection(icon.getClass().getSimpleName());\r\n      icons.put(icon.getFontFamily(), iconCollection);\r\n    }\r\n    iconCollection.add(icon);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  private static class IconCollection {\r\n    private String name;\r\n    private List<IconCode> icons;\r\n\r\n    public IconCollection(String name) {\r\n      this.name = name;\r\n      this.icons = new ArrayList<>();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public void add(IconCode icon) {\r\n      this.icons.add(icon);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public List<IconCode> getIcons() {\r\n      return icons;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public String getName() {\r\n      return name;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n  \r\n  public static IconCode showDialog(Component component, String title)  {\r\n    IconCodeDialog iconFontDialog = new IconCodeDialog();\r\n    iconFontDialog.setTitle(title);\r\n    iconFontDialog.setVisible(true);\r\n    return iconFontDialog.getSelectedIcon();\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n    IconCodeDialog iconFontDialog = new IconCodeDialog();\r\n    iconFontDialog.addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {\r\n      @Override\r\n      public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {\r\n        System.exit(0);\r\n      }\r\n    });\r\n    iconFontDialog.setVisible(true);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n```"}

I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":73047671,"created_at":"2015-05-04T15:16:18Z","updated_at":"2015-05-04T15:16:18Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/nigelht/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":708503096,"created_at":"2020-09-24T22:04:56Z","updated_at":"2021-02-14T11:00:37Z","state":"open","title":"Swing and Spring Integration","html_url":"https://github.com/HotswapProjects/HotswapAgent/issues/372","body":"Hello. \r\nThis is a question rather than an issue. (I apologize for this.)\r\n\r\nI have a spring boot desktop application (Swing).\r\nI want to change a bean which is an instance of JPanel, and reload the class. \r\n(see for full code: https://github.com/bosbeles/spring-swing-deneme)\r\n\r\nI am using Intellij. Java 8.\r\n**Problem 1:** \r\nWhen I change  constructor, and add/modify a method name, then Ctrl+Shift+F9, it is working.\r\nBut when I change only the constructor, and then Ctrl+Shift+F9; intellij shows a popup for hot code replace. But bean definition is not refreshed.\r\nHow can I force to refresh bean definition when I change only the constructor (or probably a method body).\r\n\r\n**Problem 2**\r\nAs I said before, if I change method name, it works. But this is a hack.\r\n\r\nI have modified your example plugin, and scheduled a timer with 2 seconds delay.\r\nI am holding panel instance in a map. When I change the class, I am fetching the panel bean from the application context (which is statically gotten [a bad design]).\r\nThen an action get panel from the map, and uses it.\r\nIt works because of the delay. Normally Spring plugin works after my example plugin. When I put 2 seconds delay, my example plugin works after the spring plugin. Then I can get the new, modified, refreshed bean.\r\nAs you see, there are some hacks. Is there a more appropriate way to do this? \r\n\r\n`\r\n\r\n        @OnClassFileEvent(classNameRegexp = MAIN_PANEL, events = {CREATE, MODIFY})\r\n       public void changeClassFile(String className) {\r\n        scheduler.scheduleCommand(new ReloadClassCommand(appClassLoader, className, mainPanel), 2000);\r\n       }\r\n\r\n        public static void classReloaded(String className, Object mainPanel) {\r\n\r\n        // this is the main purpose of this class. Finally, we can use typed variables and\r\n        // use normal code instead of reflection. Imagine more complex code to reload part of your\r\n        // framework - it would be inconvenient to use reflection for each invocation.\r\n        EventQueue.invokeLater(() -> {\r\n            MainFrame mainFrame = Application.context.getBean(MainFrame.class);\r\n            mainFrame.getFactory().put(\"Window 2\", Application.context.getBean(MainPanel.class));\r\n\r\n        });\r\n\r\n\r\n    }\r\n\r\n`\r\n \r\n\r\n"}

{"id":72990628,"created_at":"2015-05-04T10:54:54Z","updated_at":"2015-05-04T10:54:55Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/taoujouti/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":121056241,"created_at":"2015-12-08T17:22:39Z","updated_at":"2015-12-08T17:22:39Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/weimingtom/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":70878918,"created_at":"2015-04-25T08:52:24Z","updated_at":"2015-04-25T08:52:25Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/duongNA/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":114195705,"created_at":"2015-10-30T04:00:53Z","updated_at":"2015-10-30T04:00:53Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/Zizouz212/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}
{"id":1213766150,"created_at":"2022-04-24T20:54:48Z","updated_at":"2022-04-28T10:33:05Z","state":"open","title":"[BUG] Java Admin Client uses non-Swing concurrency to interact with GUI","html_url":"https://github.com/eXist-db/exist/issues/4355","body":"The Java Admin Client is a Swing application, and as such should follow the Swing guidelines when using multiple threads to update UI components. See - https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/concurrency/index.html\r\n\r\nTherefore we should modify the existing background tasks that use Runnable's and calls to `InteractiveClient#newClientThread(String, Runnable)` with instances of `SwingWorker`.\r\n\r\nThis also has the benefit of giving us the facility to incrementally update the UI as chunks of results become available.\r\n\r\nFor an example of how to do this, see - https://github.com/eXist-db/exist/pull/4356/commits/e3c834e0c965a7f97af106e00529ef18089984cd"}

{"id":100878361,"created_at":"2015-08-13T21:52:06Z","updated_at":"2015-08-13T21:52:06Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/rzel/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":114404482,"created_at":"2015-10-31T11:20:12Z","updated_at":"2019-04-16T01:18:07Z","state":"open","title":"OpenJDK and Swing issues","html_url":"https://github.com/IsmAvatar/LateralGM/issues/227","body":"Quick dump of issues from IRC. Repro'd on Ubuntu 15.10 with LGM 1.8.6.844.\n\nWith openjdk-8-jre:\n- Set theme to Swing and select different items in the project tree or the Object frame events tree, the renderer will be screwed up. This does not occur with tree's that do not use a custom renderer. The same issues are visible in the tree of the default open dialog under this theme.\n- Set theme to Swing and go to Help -> About, LGM will hang\n- Set theme to Native and these will cause hangs (there may be others):\n  - Open and Save dialog with JFileChooser will cause hang when navigating to a directory\n  - Object editor will cause hang when adding an action\n\nWith openjdk-7-jre/openjdk-8-jre:\n- Open progress dialog will stay on screen after open is done\n- Save progress dialog will stay on screen after save if not already on screen, and will close after save if already on screen\n\nTo mitigate, install Oracle JRE.\n"}

{"id":61267106,"created_at":"2015-03-13T22:01:06Z","updated_at":"2015-03-13T22:01:06Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/ryanqq/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":118164996,"created_at":"2015-11-21T03:03:02Z","updated_at":"2015-11-21T03:03:02Z","state":"open","title":"Standard Swing Inheritance Patterns","html_url":"https://github.com/JackWangCUMT/macwidgets/issues/182","body":"```\nThis library looks *amazing* and would dramatically improve the quality of many \nJava apps. I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":960493693,"created_at":"2021-08-04T13:56:02Z","updated_at":"2021-08-04T13:56:02Z","state":"open","title":"javax.swing.ImageIcon classloader leak","html_url":"https://github.com/mjiderhamn/classloader-leak-prevention/issues/113","body":"The class `javax.swing.ImageIcon` causes a classloader leak which is not covered yet by default (as of classloader-leak-prevention 2.7.0).\r\n\r\nSteps to reproduce:\r\n1. Build the attached example project [imageicon-leak.zip](https://github.com/mjiderhamn/classloader-leak-prevention/files/6931705/imageicon-leak.zip) (mvn clean install)\r\n2. Deploy the .war file into a Tomcat 8.5.65\r\n3. Undeploy it again\r\n\r\nThen the classloader is not garbage collected due to the following Path2GC:\r\n![imageicon-leak](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25172174/128191807-da873687-f67f-4df9-afd2-487f644fa575.png)\r\n\r\nObviously the instance of the anonymous class `javax.swing.ImageIcon$3` has a reference to an `AccessControlContext` retaining the `ParallelWebappClassLoader`. It is created at ImageIcon.java line 347 (from AdoptOpenJDK jdk8u272-b10):\r\n```java\r\n    private MediaTracker getTracker() {\r\n        Object trackerObj;\r\n        AppContext ac = AppContext.getAppContext();\r\n        // Opt: Only synchronize if trackerObj comes back null?\r\n        // If null, synchronize, re-check for null, and put new tracker\r\n        synchronized(ac) {\r\n            trackerObj = ac.get(TRACKER_KEY);\r\n            if (trackerObj == null) {\r\n                Component comp = new Component() {};   // <--- javax.swing.ImageIcon$3\r\n                trackerObj = new MediaTracker(comp);\r\n                ac.put(TRACKER_KEY, trackerObj);\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        return (MediaTracker) trackerObj;\r\n    }\r\n```\r\n\r\nAdding the following clean-up step solves this issue:\r\n\r\n```java\r\npublic class AwtMediaTrackerCleanUp implements ClassLoaderPreMortemCleanUp {\r\n\r\n    @Override\r\n    public void cleanUp(ClassLoaderLeakPreventor preventor) {\r\n        StringBuilder trackerKey = preventor.getStaticFieldValue(ImageIcon.class, \"TRACKER_KEY\");\r\n        AppContext appContext = AppContext.getAppContext();\r\n        synchronized (appContext) {\r\n            appContext.remove(trackerKey);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```"}

{"id":740575547,"created_at":"2020-11-11T08:35:03Z","updated_at":"2020-12-03T14:37:39Z","state":"open","title":"Testing Swing Code","html_url":"https://github.com/Zettelkasten-Team/Zettelkasten/issues/288","body":"Many Swing functions only work when the components are visible on screen. In these cases, your tests have to create dummy frames and show the components before the tests can succeed. \r\n\r\nIdeally, you should try to minimise the need to test Swing code from the outset. The application logic should not be intertwined with the Swing stuff. If it is provided with Swing, you don't have to test it.\r\n\r\n"}
{"id":1221905276,"created_at":"2022-04-30T19:35:42Z","updated_at":"2022-05-19T18:49:24Z","state":"open","title":"[Feature Request] Option to customize items defined as weapons for the dont-switch-during-combat config option","html_url":"https://github.com/JEFF-Media-GbR/Spigot-BestTools/issues/24","body":"I'm using a plugin that introduces axes that are designed to be used for combat, and is focused on PvE combat. This frequently leads to scenarios where I would like to be able to choose when to swing my combat axe and when to swing my sword/trident.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, the dont-switch-during-battle configuration option does not consider axes as weapons, and does not currently allow you to customize the list of items considered weapons. This leads to frequent undesired toggling of BestTools.\r\n\r\nPlease allow players to customize the 'weapons' list via the config, or provide some other way to allow axes to optionally be considered as weapons for the dont-switch-during-combat config option."}

{"id":476211645,"created_at":"2019-08-02T14:35:44Z","updated_at":"2021-06-18T00:03:00Z","state":"open","title":"Please port Swing to TeaVM","html_url":"https://github.com/konsoletyper/teavm/issues/406","body":"First of all TeaVM is such an amazing project and it should be noticed even more - porting Swing could do the trick!\r\nSwing on TeaVM (I am aware of SnapKit) is far simpler then you probably realize. \r\nIt would also not blow up the overall code one has to download. This is not the full JCL - Swing is just a tiny part.\r\nA lot of work has already been done in form of the Cacio project: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_Window_Toolkit#Implementation\r\n\r\nI've put the caciocavallo repo online for you so you can explore more easily: https://github.com/suthcark/caciocavallo\r\n\r\nCacio is a super-tiny piece of software that's comprised of:\r\n- A porting layer for AWT widgets. This implements the peer interfaces and uses Swing to provide AWT widgets. Very useful on platforms that don't provide any native widgets, or if you're simply too lazy and don't care about AWT ;-)\r\n- A windowing layer that basically provides heavyweight windowing all in Java. This implements some interfaces of the above AWT porting layer, and can provide HW windowing, for example, on systems that only have a sort of graphics/framebuffer, but no native windowing.\r\n\r\nThe above are only support layers and don't do much themselves. There are however a number of actual ports that use the above 'core' Cacio stuff, plus tons of stuff from the desktop module (namely, SunGraphics2D, SurfaceData, fonts, etc):\r\n- An SDL port\r\n- A DirectFB port\r\n- An implementation that only renders into BufferedImages and uses Robot to simulate events. This is extremely useful, and infact used for GUI testing:\r\n- An implementation that renders into an HTML5 canvas using a webbrowser, i.e. the Swing application runs on a server, client accesses it through a browser. Browser renders graphics using JavaScript/HTML5 and sends back events to the server. This is called CacioWeb\r\n\r\nFurther reading about the architecture and different implementations:\r\n\r\nInitial Proposal: http://mail.openjdk.java.net/pipermail/challenge-discuss/2008-March/000082.html\r\nhttp://rkennke.wordpress.com/2008/12/18/caciocavallo-architecture-overview/\r\nhttp://rkennke.wordpress.com/2008/09/03/cacio-swing-awt-peers/\r\nhttp://mail.openjdk.java.net/pipermail/caciocavallo-dev/2009-September/000184.html\r\nhttp://rkennke.wordpress.com/2011/07/28/jdk7-and-cacio-coolness/\r\nhttp://www.webcitation.org/1312943154337056\r\nhttp://rkennke.wordpress.com/2012/05/02/caciocavallo-1-1-released/\r\nhttp://rkennke.wordpress.com/2012/12/12/quick-cacio-web-howto/\r\n\r\n\r\nThe OpenJDK project caciocavallo dissolved just this month but it will come back to Github soon: https://mail.openjdk.java.net/pipermail/caciocavallo-dev/2019-June/000573.html\r\n\r\nCacio is also available in Maven Central and some of its implementations are part of other projects on Github:\r\nhttps://mvnrepository.com/artifact/net.java.openjdk.cacio\r\nhttps://github.com/iaavo/provolone\r\nhttps://github.com/UISpec4J/UISpec4J"}

I find myself lusting after many of these widgets because there are \nsimply no satisfying alternatives in Swing or SwingX.\n\nHowever, although I understand the sentiment and simplicity of use for your \nAPI, your widgets do not follow the same bean pattern as core Swing components. \nThis means that GUI Editors - such as the Netbeans one - cannot use your \nwidgets.\n\nPlease release a version which has Swing style patterns so that they can be \ndrag and dropped into Netbeans GUI Editor.\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Sam.Hall...@gmail.com` on 31 May 2012 at 10:07\n"}

{"id":1130392000,"created_at":"2022-02-10T16:11:49Z","updated_at":"2022-02-12T03:05:40Z","state":"open","title":"Reconsider directory structure","html_url":"https://github.com/openrocket/openrocket/issues/1115","body":"When the source directory was separated into .../core and .../swing, the result wasn't very clean.  Some examples:\r\nParts database is in swing.\r\nMaster build script for final .jar is in swing.\r\nInsertion of project-wide metafiles into jar is in core.\r\n\r\nThis can (and should) be cleaned up.\r\n"}
{"id":1201328707,"created_at":"2022-04-12T07:46:51Z","updated_at":"2022-04-21T10:47:37Z","state":"open","title":"Set availability of certain Layouts","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/windowbuilder/issues/181","body":"We need the ability to hide/show certain layouts. This should affect the layouts displayed in the context menu, designer palette and the dropdown list. \r\n\r\nFor example a user should be able to specify what layouts should be available in a preference page, this should include layouts of Swing and SWT. If a user selects, say Border Layout and BoxLayout from the Swing layouts preference page and FillLayout and Form Layout from the SWT layouts page. Only these layouts should be available to use by the user."}

{"id":228202910,"created_at":"2017-05-12T06:51:07Z","updated_at":"2017-08-09T15:51:31Z","state":"open","title":"Assertj-Swing: GuiActionRunner - numRetries/waitBetweenRetries","html_url":"https://github.com/assertj/assertj-swing/issues/204","body":"Hi,\r\nunfortunately i miss following feature. I have the problem that some actions creating a new GUI form/element runs a lot of time (SwingWorker, DynamicTreeNode(s)). So i implemented following workaround, which works fine.\r\n\r\nExample\r\n   public static void execute(@Nonnull GuiTask task) {\r\n        if (!executeInEDT) {\r\n            executeInCurrentThread(task);\r\n            return;\r\n        }\r\n        for (int i = 0; i < # ConfigAssertJ.numRetries - 1; i++) {\r\n            run(task);\r\n            if (task.catchedException() == null) {\r\n                break;\r\n            }\r\n            // Error -> retry\r\n            System.out.println(\"Retry \" + task);\r\n            try {\r\n                Thread.sleep(ConfigAssertJ.waitBetweenRetries);\r\n            } catch (Exception e) {\r\n                // TODO: handle exception\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        rethrowCaughtExceptionIn(task);\r\n    }"}

{"id":1121066393,"created_at":"2022-02-01T18:38:39Z","updated_at":"2022-05-16T11:02:29Z","state":"open","title":"8185261: Font fallback sometimes doesn't work in Swing text components","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/7313","body":"The proposed fix makes fonts with and without fallback components distinguishable (in terms of `equals` method), so that\r\nfont metrics cache (and other similar code) can handle them separately. This is achieved by adding a new boolean field\r\nto `Font` class, specifically denoting fonts with fallback components. The latter ones don't need to pretend to be\r\n'created' fonts anymore, to preserve their `Font2D` handle.\r\nIt's not possible to use the existing `createdFont` field in `equals` implementation, as JCK requires a 'real' created\r\nfont (the one obtained using `Font.createFont` method) to be equal to the same font after serialization and\r\ndeserialization.\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n- [ ] Change must be properly reviewed\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8185261](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8185261): Font fallback sometimes doesn't work in Swing text components\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7313/head:pull/7313` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7313`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/7313` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/7313/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 7313`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 7313`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7313.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/7313.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":520774537,"created_at":"2019-11-11T06:57:20Z","updated_at":"2020-03-29T11:01:23Z","state":"open","title":"Migrating From Swing to JavaFX ?","html_url":"https://github.com/RalfBarkow/ZettelkastenFX/issues/1","body":"Robillard, Martin P., and Kaylee Kutschera. ‚ÄûLessons Learned in Migrating From Swing to JavaFX‚Äú. IEEE Software, 2019, 1‚Äì1. https://doi.org/10.1109/MS.2019.2919840.\r\n\r\nAbstract:\r\nThe authors describe a case study of the migration of an interactive diagramming tool written in Java from the Swing Graphical User Interface framework to the more recent JavaFX framework. The study distills the authors‚Äô experience identifying what information was needed to support the migration effort, and how the information was ultimately discovered. The outcome is presented in a set of five lessons about the discrepancies between expectations and reality in the search for information when migrating software between major frameworks."}

{"id":808971764,"created_at":"2021-02-16T04:24:07Z","updated_at":"2022-04-03T08:26:56Z","state":"open","title":"Idiot-proof the error messages in swing gui","html_url":"https://github.com/FabricMC/fabric-loader/issues/386","body":"It has come to my attention on discord from shedaniel and the Origins discord server that apparently people do not typically want to read and try to understand the error messages that show up on the swing gui for mod dependency issues.\r\n\r\nTypically most people seeing this GUI are users, hence they do not need the developer cruft.\r\n\r\nEssentially the solution here is to cut out all the developer cruft from the error messages (probably just dropping them into a dropdown box) and simplify the messages into:\r\n\r\n`You need to install X`, `You need to upgrade X to version 2.0.0`, `X breaks Y, you need to remove one of these`.\r\n\r\nIf we want dev text, it may be better then to either display the full fat thing in a dev environment or make people pass some sort of `-DBigBrain` to see the verbose developer text."}
{"id":1249315686,"created_at":"2022-05-26T09:18:56Z","updated_at":"2022-05-26T12:00:37Z","state":"open","title":"8272707: Resolving URI relative path with no / may lead to incorrect toString","html_url":"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/8899","body":"Consider an authority component without trailing \"/\" as a base URI. When resolving a relative path against this base URI, the resulting URI is a concatenated URI without \"/\".\r\nThis behaviour should be fixed, which is rationalized by rfc3986#section-5.2.3.\r\nCould you review this fix?\n\n<!-- Anything below this marker will be automatically updated, please do not edit manually! -->\n---------\n### Progress\n- [ ] Change must be properly reviewed (1 review required, with at least 1 [Reviewer](https://openjdk.java.net/bylaws#reviewer))\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\n- [x] Commit message must refer to an issue\n\n### Integration blocker\n&nbsp;‚ö†Ô∏è Title mismatch between PR and JBS for issue [JDK-8272707](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8272707)\n\n### Issue\n * [JDK-8272707](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8272707): Swing components and fonts incorrectly sized in Windows LAF on scaled display ‚ö†Ô∏è Title mismatch between PR and JBS.\n\n\n### Reviewing\n<details><summary>Using <code>git<\/code><\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git fetch https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8899/head:pull/8899` \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8899`\n\nUpdate a local copy of the PR: \\\n`$ git checkout pull/8899` \\\n`$ git pull https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk pull/8899/head`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using Skara CLI tools<\/summary>\n\nCheckout this PR locally: \\\n`$ git pr checkout 8899`\n\nView PR using the GUI difftool: \\\n`$ git pr show -t 8899`\n\n<\/details>\n<details><summary>Using diff file<\/summary>\n\nDownload this PR as a diff file: \\\n<a href=\"https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8899.diff\">https://git.openjdk.java.net/jdk/pull/8899.diff<\/a>\n\n<\/details>\n"}

{"id":500470439,"created_at":"2019-09-30T19:19:01Z","updated_at":"2019-10-01T08:35:04Z","state":"open","title":"SWING Table view needs improvements","html_url":"https://github.com/adempiere/adempiere/issues/2836","body":"The SWING table view allows the user to see a number of records at once.  While it looks like a spreadsheet, it doesn't behave like one. There are a number of frustrating little issues:\r\n\r\n- When the table is first opened, its not apparent which cell has the focus. Hitting tab has no effect unless the user is persistent. In the Business Partner window in GardenWorld, the user has to hit tab about 35 times for the focus to appear.\r\n- Navigation through the data is inconsistent. The arrow keys should move the focus around easily but the key bindings trap the left,right arrow keys when the cell is an editable text field,  Same with the Enter key. When navigating, the enter key or Shift-Enter should move the focus up or down but editable fields will prevent this, trapping the focus.\r\n\r\nI'm partly to blame for this. In #2471, I proposed a change to make the cell with the focus immediately editable.  While this does work, it causes the above issues.\r\n\r\nI'd like to modify this to provide the following behaviour.\r\n\r\nFocus: some visible cell should always have the focus.  The focus should move according to the following key bindings:\r\n\r\n| Behaviour  |  Keys |\r\n|  --- | --- |\r\n| Select the cell to the right | Tab or Right Arrow |\r\n| Select the cell to the left | Shift-Tab or Left Arrow |\r\n| Select the cell below | Enter or Down Arrow or Down icon button|\r\n| Select the cell above | Shift-Enter or UP Arrow |\r\n| Select the first cell in the current row | Home |\r\n| Select the last cell in the current  row | End |\r\n| Select the first cell in the current column | Ctrl-Home |\r\n| Select the last cell in the current column | Ctrl-End |\r\n| Edit the cell | Any character key or Mouse click in the cell |\r\n| Delete the cell contents (set the value to null) and edit the cell | Delete |\r\n| Cancel any edits on a row | Escape |\r\n\r\nWhen any character key is typed, the cell editor should be invoked and that character be added to the editor.\r\n\r\nOnce editing a cell, the behaviour should change as follows:\r\n\r\n| Behaviour  |  Keys |\r\n|  --- | --- |\r\n| Add a character  | Type any character key |\r\n| Delete the previous character | Delete |\r\n| Move the caret | Left or Right arrow or click in the text |\r\n| Move caret to the first position | Home |\r\n| Move caret to the last position | End |\r\n| Bind the data, stop editing and move to the cell below | Enter |\r\n| Bind the data, stop editing and move to the next cell in the row | Tab |\r\n| Bind the data, stop editing | Mouse click anywhere outside the cell or use Ctrl-Home or Ctrl-End |\r\n| Cancel any edits, revert to the original value and stop editing | Escape |\r\n|For checkbox editors, select the checkbox | Space |\r\n\r\nFollowing these rules would make the table view much easier to navigate.\r\n"}

{"id":815530839,"created_at":"2021-02-24T14:28:39Z","updated_at":"2021-03-24T16:33:19Z","state":"open","title":"Increase speed of finding components in large swing hierarchy.","html_url":"https://github.com/assertj/assertj-swing/pull/261","body":"We have a large swing hierarchy with many thousands of components. \r\n\r\nThe find is VERY slow because while doing a depth first search of the hierarchy all recursive loops and match checks are queued for the swing thread and block until done.\r\n\r\nThis change causes the entire search to be done with just a single blocking invocation on the swing thread. This significantly improves the time needed to do a search on the hierarchy.\r\n\r\n\r\n"}

Depending on your contributor status for OpenJDK, please use the [JDK bug system]() or the appropriate [mailing list](http://mail.openjdk.java.net/mailman/listinfo) for the given problem area or update project [jdk8u-dev](http://mail.openjdk.java.net/mailman/listinfo/jdk8u-dev).\r\n\r\nIf your issue is specific to Corretto 8,\r\nthen you are in the right place.\r\nPlease proceed with the following.\r\n\r\n### Describe the bug\r\nWhen attempting to display Korean Characters in Swing with font \"DotumChe\" with Bold style, there are 2 issues when comparing with Oracle JDK7 in Swing.\r\n1) The drawing liner is wider than Oracle JDK 7.\r\n2) Some characters are failed to be rendering bold (partially)Ôºåcheck the third char below\r\n\r\n### To Reproduce\r\nHere is the code to reproduce.\r\n\r\n```\r\npublic class FontTestClass extends JFrame {\r\n\r\n  public FontTestClass() {\r\n    \r\n    JLabel jl = new JLabel(\"Ï†Ñ ÎØ∏Ìñ• ÏïàÏ£ºÌòÑ\");\r\n    // DotumChe\r\n    Font font = new Font(\"DotumChe\", Font.BOLD, 120);\r\n    jl.setFont(font);\r\n    setTitle(System.getProperty(\"java.version\") + \" Font : \" + font.getName() + \" Style : \" + font.isBold()); //$NON-NLS-1$\r\n    this.setLayout(null);\r\n    setSize(3100, 1100);// 400 width and 500 height\r\n    jl.setBounds(130, 100, 3100, 1100);// x axis, y axis, width, height\r\n    this.add(jl);\r\n    this.setVisible(true); \r\n  }\r\n\r\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n    new FontTestClass();\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\nSee the screenshot below when running above code against Oracle JDK7\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/56990955/120410095-ae7e7a80-c395-11eb-9300-ff3b81b53127.png)\r\n\r\n### Screenshots\r\nSee the screenshot below when running above code against OpenJDK8\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/56990955/120410153-c655fe80-c395-11eb-8796-b8c37e04d382.png)\r\n\r\n### Platform information\r\n    OS: Windows 10 + DotumChe installed\r\n    Version: \r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/56990955/120410240-ef768f00-c395-11eb-9e1f-2752afbf32c5.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n### Additional context\r\nMake sure font \"DotumChe\" being installed before testing\r\n\r\nFor VM crashes, please attach the error report file. By default the file name is `hs_err_pidpid.log`, where pid is the process ID of the process."}

{"id":94277433,"created_at":"2015-07-10T10:28:10Z","updated_at":"2015-07-10T10:28:10Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/nishaaggarwal/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}
