{"id":372184034,"created_at":"2018-10-20T07:31:37Z","updated_at":"2021-09-13T08:37:22Z","state":"open","title":"Swing Console: Celsius/Fahrenheit switch is broken","html_url":"https://github.com/home-climate-control/dz/issues/62","body":"How to reproduce: Press `C` or `F` key (command to switch between Celsius and Fahrenheit display) while the focus is on DZ Swing Console. Watch the grid change. After several sensor inputs, press it again.\r\n\r\nExpected result:\r\n- Numbers on display change to reflect the new measurement unit;\r\n- The grid changes its view to reflect new measurement unit;\r\n- Temperature chart stays more or less the same.\r\n\r\nActual result:\r\n- Numbers on display change to reflect the new measurement unit;\r\n- Temperature chart shifts down (if changing from `C` to `F`) and stays there; however, new values are properly matched against the grid;\r\n- Grid autoscaling breaks because it now covers the range from `C` to `F` absolute values;\r\n- The display will stay this way until 3 hours plus autoscaling adjustment interval pass.\r\n\r\n"}
{"id":108476373,"created_at":"2015-09-26T15:41:45Z","updated_at":"2016-08-26T09:29:22Z","state":"open","title":"[do not yet merge] Refactor EventSource","html_url":"https://github.com/ReactiveX/RxSwing/pull/29","body":"While working on #28, I noticed that there's quite some code duplication in this project which could be eliminated.\n\nMy solution is to factor out the common code into an abstract class `EventSource`, and into `SwingObservable.create`.\n\nYou will observe that some of my new `XxxEventSource` classes implement the `addListenerForComponent`/`removeListenerFromComponent` methods, while others don't. The reason for this irregularity is that there are two kinds of Swing events:\n-    The easy ones: All Swing classes supporting such events share a common superclass or interface with an `addXxxListener` and `removeXxxListener` method. Examples: All Swing classes supporting `KeyEvent` inherit from `Component`, and all Swing classes supporting `ItemEvent` implement `ItemSelectable`.\n-    The tricky ones: There's no such a common superclass or interface for all Swing classes supporting the event. Examples: `ActionEvent`, `ChangeEvent`.\n\nMy solution works for both of them, and is only slightly more verbose for the tricky ones.\n\nConsider this PR as a preview. I've only performed the refactoring for a few event sources, and before we do it for all of them, I'd like to know what others think of it.\n"}

{"id":1034087468,"created_at":"2021-10-23T06:02:37Z","updated_at":"2022-05-06T08:18:08Z","state":"open","title":"Re-implement SciaReto with JavaFX","html_url":"https://github.com/raydac/netbeans-mmd-plugin/issues/88","body":"Have you considered that re-implement the SciaReto with JavaFX? I know it means a lot of effort to achieve that and this probably an excessive request. I just want to know how you think about it or what's your planning.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you want to know why I suggest this, here are the reasons that I can think up:\r\n1. Modern UI than Swing/AWT and easy to customize. \r\n2. Less code and easier to maintain.\r\n3. Since Swing/AWT was deprecated, remaining bugs and new bugs won't be fixed.\r\n4. Compatible with Swing which means not everything needs to be rebuilded. \r\n5. Easier to accomplish some advanced features like Dark Mode theme(may be I guess).\r\n\r\nSince I use SciaReto as a personal knowledge base, I use it almost everyday, it is really a very good and useful tool, I'd like to see it becomes better and better.\r\n\r\nThanks"}

{"id":866507688,"created_at":"2021-04-24T00:42:08Z","updated_at":"2021-04-24T00:42:08Z","state":"open","title":"FYI: Hugely useful for Swing as well","html_url":"https://github.com/0x4a616e/NSMenuFX/issues/16","body":"FYI, this line:\r\n\r\n`MenuToolkit.toolkit().setAppearanceMode(AppearanceMode.DARK);`\r\n\r\n...works with Swing as well. Combining that one line with the following:\r\n\r\nhttps://www.formdev.com/flatlaf/\r\n\r\n...and (amazingly) the following line...\r\n\r\n`System.setProperty(\"apple.laf.useScreenMenuBar\", \"true\");`\r\n\r\n...is now giving me an astonishingly modern looking Swing app on macOS, with IntelliJ-style theme options, macOS menu bar, and window decorations that match the OS.\r\n\r\nI'd suggest updating the documentation to reflect that the library is *hugely* useful for Swing as well as JavaFX.\r\n\r\nAlso, P.S. thanks for this - very helpful!"}

{"id":142837858,"created_at":"2016-03-23T02:10:15Z","updated_at":"2016-03-23T02:10:15Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/HemaNage/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":543525410,"created_at":"2019-12-29T19:05:58Z","updated_at":"2022-02-15T19:34:55Z","state":"open","title":"[Needs Thinking] Consistency between InstrumentSettings and Swing after user input.","html_url":"https://github.com/jandejongh/jinstrument/issues/6","body":"[AbstractInstrument] At the present time, user input on an [Swing] Instrument View typically results in an applicable \"request\" to the Instrument. If the request results in a change in Instrument Settings, the implementation of AbstractInstrument will report the new Instrument Settings to its listeners, and as a result the Instrument View Swing state will be updated.\r\nHowever, some user interactions result in an immediate change in Swing components, and if the \"request\" did not result in different Instrument Settings, the component is not informed about it because AbstractInstrument only propagates changes to the Instrument Settings.\r\nAs a result, the Swing component is left in an inconsistent state.\r\nA solution could be to inform AbstractInstrument that a specific listener wants ALL readings of the InstrumentSettings, instead of just the \"deltas\"."}

= 0;\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\tif(count <= 0) {\r\n\t\t\tcount = 0;\r\n\t\t\torderTableModel.addRow(new Object[] {menu, ++count, money}); //ÌñâÏ∂îÍ∞Ä\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t} else {\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\tint {"id":142131937,"created_at":"2016-03-20T05:41:30Z","updated_at":"2016-03-20T05:41:30Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/Lyn-Tech/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":311554007,"created_at":"2018-04-05T10:23:17Z","updated_at":"2018-04-05T10:23:17Z","state":"open","title":"Swing Components are incompatiable with Launch4J.","html_url":"https://github.com/ElliotAlexander/seg-runway-redeclaration-tool/issues/8","body":"I've moved our build process over to wrapping the executable jar into an exe, using Launch4J. For reasons I've not been able to figure out, native Swing components seem to crash out the Launch4J wrapper. We seem to use them sparsely, and I've refactored the ones we were using, but just a note to say don't use them from this point onwards!"}

{"id":132370337,"created_at":"2016-02-09T09:31:45Z","updated_at":"2016-02-09T09:31:45Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/gBroutin/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":993056950,"created_at":"2021-09-10T09:28:15Z","updated_at":"2021-09-13T07:41:08Z","state":"open","title":"Eliminate dependency on Swing and call to invokeLater","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/visualvm/pull/345","body":"There is a support for reporting progress of long running operations via the  `HeapProgress` class. However this class directly calls into AWT which would better be avoided if the librrary is supposed to be used in a  _headless mode_.\r\n\r\nThis PR keeps the compatibility with existing `HeapProgress` behavior, yet it avoid the AWT interactions until somebody access `HeapProgress.getProgress()` model."}

                                        \r\n   \r\n    private void jTextField_codigoKeyPressed(java.awt.event.KeyEvent evt) {                                             \r\n        // TODO add your handling code here:\r\n         if(evt.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_ENTER){\r\n               int pesquisaCodigo = Integer.parseInt(jTextField_codigo.getText());\r\n        try{ \r\n      \r\n         \r\n        conecta.executaSQL(\" select * from produto where id_produto='\"+pesquisaCodigo+\"'\");\r\n        conecta.rs.first();\r\n          jTextField_produto.setText(conecta.rs.getString(\"descricao\"));\r\n          jTextField_valor.setText(String.valueOf(conecta.rs.getDouble(\"preco_venda\")));\r\n          \r\n            //pst.getString(jTextField_produto.setText(sql));\r\n       \r\n        }catch(SQLException exx){\r\n            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null,\"erro:  \"+ exx);\r\n            \r\n        } \r\n         \r\n         \r\n         }\r\n    }                                            \r\n      /**\r\n     * @param args the command line arguments\r\n     */\r\n    \r\n    public void PreencherTabela(String SQL){\r\n        ArrayList dados = new ArrayList();\r\n        \r\n        String [] Colunas = new String[]{\"Codigo\",\"Descri√ß√£o\",\"Quantidade\",\"Valor venda\"};\r\n    \r\n        conecta.executaSQL(SQL);\r\n        try {\r\n            conecta.rs.first();\r\n         do{\r\n             dados.add(new Object[]{conecta.rs.getInt(\"id_produto\"),conecta.rs.getString(\"descricao\"),conecta.rs.getInt(\"quantidade\"),conecta.rs.getInt(\"quantidade_min\"),conecta.rs.getDouble(\"preco_compra\"),conecta.rs.getDouble(\"preco_venda\")});\r\n             \r\n           }while(conecta.rs.next());\r\n        } catch (SQLException eeex) {\r\n            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null,\"erro ao preencher\"+ eeex);\r\n        }\r\n                \r\n        ModeloTabela modelo = new ModeloTabela(dados, Colunas);\r\n        jTable_venda.setModel(modelo);\r\n        jTable_venda.getColumnModel().getColumn(0).setPreferredWidth(120);\r\n {"id":95595844,"created_at":"2015-07-17T06:18:10Z","updated_at":"2015-07-17T06:18:10Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/akuche/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

See the changes in this this commit.\r\nhttps://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/pull/62/commits/40f303404ea6e21ac1c5710140582110732fa2bf\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/37407705/79948168-9f7b8800-8473-11ea-9596-7433a3fe12d0.png)\r\nLeft is Swing, right is JavaFX. (without the fix)\r\n\r\n2. In the same screenshot, you can see the left plot has a joined domain axis, whereas the left one does not. Both plots are an instance of CombinedDomainXYPlot. The gap is set to 0 on creation of both of those charts. In Swing it works, in java fx it does not. For some reason though, if the plot is cloned, moved to a new window and then a theme is applied, the axis join.\r\n\r\nI hope this is enough information, if you need to know more please let me know.\r\n\r\nBest regards\r\nSteffen"}

{"id":70270309,"created_at":"2015-04-23T00:37:27Z","updated_at":"2015-04-23T00:37:27Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/anubhav94/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":306810130,"created_at":"2018-03-20T10:38:15Z","updated_at":"2018-03-20T10:38:15Z","state":"open","title":"CheckBoxTree ClassCastException after setModel()","html_url":"https://github.com/jidesoft/jide-oss/issues/28","body":"We use a customized treemodel that implements `TreeModel` that does not work with `TreeNode `objects.\r\n\r\nIf we used the TreeModel constructor, everthing works fine:\r\n`cbtMain = new CheckBoxTree(new PositionenTreeModel(angebot, AngebotPosition.all(angebot)));`\r\n\r\nBut if we used the empty constructor with following setModel(), a ClassCastException is thrown:\r\n```\r\ncbtMain = new CheckBoxTree();\r\ncbtMain.setModel(new PositionenTreeModel(angebot, AngebotPosition.all(angebot)));\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nException in thread \"main\" java.lang.ClassCastException: de.rekers.ft._incubator.Angebot cannot be cast to javax.swing.tree.TreeNode\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.DefaultTreeModel.getChildCount(DefaultTreeModel.java:186)\r\n\tat com.jidesoft.swing.CheckBoxTreeSelectionModel.getChildrenCount(CheckBoxTreeSelectionModel.java:557)\r\n\tat com.jidesoft.swing.CheckBoxTreeSelectionModel.isPathSelected(CheckBoxTreeSelectionModel.java:169)\r\n\tat com.jidesoft.swing.CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.updateCheckBoxState(CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.java:139)\r\n\tat com.jidesoft.swing.CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.getTreeCellRendererComponent(CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.java:99)\r\n\tat javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicTreeUI$NodeDimensionsHandler.getNodeDimensions(BasicTreeUI.java:2807)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.AbstractLayoutCache.getNodeDimensions(AbstractLayoutCache.java:492)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache$TreeStateNode.updatePreferredSize(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:1360)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache$TreeStateNode.expand(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:1473)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache$TreeStateNode.expand(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:1288)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache.rebuild(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:743)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache.setModel(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:109)\r\n\tat javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicTreeUI.setModel(BasicTreeUI.java:412)\r\n\tat javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicTreeUI$Handler.propertyChange(BasicTreeUI.java:3414)\r\n\tat java.beans.PropertyChangeSupport.fire(PropertyChangeSupport.java:335)\r\n\tat java.beans.PropertyChangeSupport.firePropertyChange(PropertyChangeSupport.java:327)\r\n\tat java.beans.PropertyChangeSupport.firePropertyChange(PropertyChangeSupport.java:263)\r\n\tat java.awt.Component.firePropertyChange(Component.java:8428)\r\n\tat javax.swing.JTree.setModel(JTree.java:882)\r\n\tat de.rekers.ft.app.angebotsverwaltung.AngebotPositionAuswahl.initUI(AngebotPositionAuswahl.java:50)\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf 'rootVisible()' is set to false, no exception is thrown.\r\n\r\nOur treemodel is not using 'DefaultTreeModel' but 'de.rekers.ft._incubator.Angebot'. It seems, that the old model from the empty constructor is accessing nodes from the new model.\r\n\r\nSince we use a GUI-Designer, we need to use the standard constructor and set the model with `setModel()`."}

{"id":111970857,"created_at":"2015-10-17T16:12:56Z","updated_at":"2015-10-17T16:12:56Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/pacificIT/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}
{"id":61245676,"created_at":"2015-03-13T21:16:31Z","updated_at":"2015-03-13T21:16:31Z","state":"open","title":"Switch from \"threads + sleep\" to swing timers.","html_url":"https://github.com/netbrain/ntorrent/issues/124","body":"```\nIn TorrentTable plugin, we are using a normal thread with a sleep of 2\nseconds for refreshing the contents of TorrentTable and depending plugins.\n\ninstead it should use swing timers.\nhttp://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/uiswing/misc/timer.html\n\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `kei...@gmail.com` on 20 Nov 2009 at 8:47\n"}

{"id":66124323,"created_at":"2015-04-03T10:48:15Z","updated_at":"2015-04-03T10:48:15Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/adityashimoga/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

Would be better to use IJ2, which also requires upgrading some IJ2 UI capabilities.\n"}
{"id":118573989,"created_at":"2015-11-24T10:14:48Z","updated_at":"2015-11-24T10:14:48Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/ManuraNirmal/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":306810130,"created_at":"2018-03-20T10:38:15Z","updated_at":"2018-03-20T10:38:15Z","state":"open","title":"CheckBoxTree ClassCastException after setModel()","html_url":"https://github.com/jidesoft/jide-oss/issues/28","body":"We use a customized treemodel that implements `TreeModel` that does not work with `TreeNode `objects.\r\n\r\nIf we used the TreeModel constructor, everthing works fine:\r\n`cbtMain = new CheckBoxTree(new PositionenTreeModel(angebot, AngebotPosition.all(angebot)));`\r\n\r\nBut if we used the empty constructor with following setModel(), a ClassCastException is thrown:\r\n```\r\ncbtMain = new CheckBoxTree();\r\ncbtMain.setModel(new PositionenTreeModel(angebot, AngebotPosition.all(angebot)));\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nException in thread \"main\" java.lang.ClassCastException: de.rekers.ft._incubator.Angebot cannot be cast to javax.swing.tree.TreeNode\r\n\tat com.jidesoft.swing.CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.getTreeCellRendererComponent(CheckBoxTreeCellRenderer.java:99)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache.rebuild(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:743)\r\n\tat javax.swing.tree.VariableHeightLayoutCache.setModel(VariableHeightLayoutCache.java:109)\r\n\tat javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicTreeUI.setModel(BasicTreeUI.java:412)\r\n\tat javax.swing.plaf.basic.BasicTreeUI$Handler.propertyChange(BasicTreeUI.java:3414)\r\n\tat java.beans.PropertyChangeSupport.firePropertyChange(PropertyChangeSupport.java:263)\r\n\tat java.awt.Component.firePropertyChange(Component.java:8428)\r\n\tat javax.swing.JTree.setModel(JTree.java:882)\r\n\tat de.rekers.ft.app.angebotsverwaltung.AngebotPositionAuswahl.initUI(AngebotPositionAuswahl.java:50)\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf 'rootVisible()' is set to false, no exception is thrown.\r\n\r\nOur treemodel is not using 'DefaultTreeModel' but 'de.rekers.ft._incubator.Angebot'. It seems, that the old model from the empty constructor is accessing nodes from the new model.\r\n\r\nSince we use a GUI-Designer, we need to use the standard constructor and set the model with `setModel()`."}

{"id":270397524,"created_at":"2017-11-01T18:03:00Z","updated_at":"2017-11-01T18:03:00Z","state":"open","title":"Rendering: Swing vs LwJGL or both?","html_url":"https://github.com/evolvio4all/evolvio4Java/issues/12","body":"With the LwJGL support on it's way (thanks @quete12!), I thought it would be nice to discuss whether we want to use both Swing and LwJGL or just one?\r\n\r\nThere's a lot to discuss and get consistent if we go with both, eg. how we combine the Renderer classes to get a consistent pipeline, how we work with the different threading strategies that Swing and our own LwJGL engine would use, how we create and manage the different supporting connections from our engine to each rendering system.\r\n\r\nMy thoughts are that supporting both is probably more effort than is worth it and we just choose one. Swing looks simpler to start with but LwJGL looks superior in the long run. It also depends on what we want from it too. Are we looking to build a simple 2D engine that's easy to change but fairly fixed in what it can do? Or a 3D engine that might be more difficult but is more flexible and powerful?\r\n\r\nPersonally I'd like to go with the 3D difficult/flexible/powerful option but am happy with either. The only thing I'd suggest is if we want to do both that we fork it to a Java2D and a Java3D sub repo."}

{"id":145368698,"created_at":"2016-04-02T12:28:04Z","updated_at":"2016-04-02T12:28:04Z","state":"open","title":"Memory Leak using org.gstreamer.swing.VideoComponent","html_url":"https://github.com/elzaksspro/gstreamer-java/issues/142","body":"```\nOS: Windows 7 64, 32-bit jdk/jre7\nGstreamer-Java: Trunk\n\nI might be running an atypical application, however it seems my Java \nApplication eventually runs out of memory after about a dozen runs.\n\nThis current application calls for simultaneous videos, and the ability to \nchoose different videos. I am then adding and removing the VideoComponents as \nneeded from my JPanels.\n\nUsing jvisualvm it seems that there are listeners preventing the GC from \ncleaning up the classes.\n\nAlbeit not pretty, to obtain a clean bill of health I had to add a method to \nclean up these things.\n\npublic void destroy() {\n        renderComponent.removePropertyChangeListener(propListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeMouseMotionListener(mouseListener);\n        renderComponent.removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeKeyListener(keyListener);\n        removeComponentListener(componentAdapter);\n        remove(renderComponent);\n        resourceTimer.removeActionListener(resourceReaper);\n        resourceTimer.stop();\n        videosink.removeListener();\n    }\n\nAttached is a TestCase that shows my issue as well as the patch. \n\nAlso looking at a similar thread \n(https://groups.google.com/d/topic/gstreamer-java/j207a4GpZa8/discussion) I am \ntrying to investigate if we should disconnect listeners before disposing the \nobjects.\n\nThanks,\nMichael Esemplare\n\n```\n\nOriginal issue reported on code.google.com by `Michael....@gmail.com` on 17 Jun 2014 at 5:36\n\nAttachments:\n- [VideoComponentGCTest.java](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponentGCTest.java)\n- [VideoComponent.java.patch](https://storage.googleapis.com/google-code-attachments/gstreamer-java/issue-142/comment-0/VideoComponent.java.patch)\n"}

{"id":1139403665,"created_at":"2022-02-16T01:16:50Z","updated_at":"2022-02-16T01:16:52Z","state":"open","title":"Bump postgresql from 42.2.5 to 42.3.3 in /Twinkle/Swing","html_url":"https://github.com/DonkeyRit/Twinkle/pull/15","body":"Bumps [postgresql](https://github.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc) from 42.2.5 to 42.3.3.\n<details>\n<summary>Changelog<\/summary>\n<p><em>Sourced from <a href=\"https://github.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md\">postgresql's changelog<\/a>.<\/em><\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<h1>Changelog<\/h1>\n<p>Notable changes since version 42.0.0, read the complete <a href=\"https://jdbc.postgresql.org/documentation/changelog.html\">History of Changes<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>The format is based on <a href=\"http://keepachangelog.com/en/1.0.0/\">Keep a Changelog<\/a>.<\/p>\n<h2>[Unreleased]<\/h2>\n<h3>Changed<\/h3>\n<h3>Added<\/h3>\n<h3>Fixed<\/h3>\n<p>[42.3.3] (2022-02-15 11:32:24 -0500)<\/p>\n<h3>Changed<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li>fix: Removed loggerFile and loggerLevel configuration. While the properties still exist.\nThey can no longer be used to configure the driver logging. Instead use java.util.logging\nconfiguration mechanisms such as <code>logging.properties<\/code>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3>Added<\/h3>\n<h3>Fixed<\/h3>\n<p>[42.3.2] (2022-02-01 07:35:41 -0500)<\/p>\n<h3>Security<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li>CVE-2022-21724 pgjdbc instantiates plugin instances based on class names provided via authenticationPluginClassName,\nsslhostnameverifier, socketFactory, sslfactory, sslpasswordcallback connection properties.\nHowever, the driver did not verify if the class implements the expected interface before instantiating the class. This\nwould allow a malicious class to be instantiated that could execute arbitrary code from the JVM. Fixed in <a href=\"https://github.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/commit/f4d0ed69c0b3aae8531d83d6af4c57f22312c813\">commit<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3>Changed<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li>perf: read in_hot_standby GUC on {"id":392610150,"created_at":"2018-12-19T13:50:00Z","updated_at":"2020-05-14T16:21:52Z","state":"open","title":"Add PlotService to SciJava","html_url":"https://github.com/scijava/scijava-ui-swing/pull/43","body":"I split the PlotService as discussed with @ctrueden recently. It now consist of three parts:\r\n* A maven artifact org.scijava;scijava-plot which has no additional dependencies\r\n* Viewer in scijava-ui-swing that depends on JFreeChart (This PR)\r\n* Converters in imagej-legacy for converting a plot to ImagePlus or Img.\r\n\r\nI might have overused converters a bit, what do you think? There are the following converters\r\n1. XYPlot -> JFreeChart (part of scijava-ui-swing)\r\n2. CategoryChart -> JFreeChart (part of scijava-ui-swing)\r\n3. Plot -> java.awt.image.BufferedImage (based on converters 1 and 2, part of scijava-ui-swing)\r\n4. Plot -> ImagePlus (based converter 3, part of imagej-legacy)\r\n5. Plot -> Img (based on converter 4, part of imagej-legacy)\r\nThe converters 1 and 2 are used to display the plot using ChartPanel of JFreeChart.\r\nThe converters 4 and 5 are there because they do what users want: Convert a plot into a datatype that they know like ImagePlus or Img.\r\nThe converter 3 exists to make imagej-legacy independent of JFreeChart.\r\n\r\nThis is what I think needs to be done to get plot service released:\r\n- [ ] Release scijava-plot\r\n  - [ ] Review https://github.com/maarzt/scijava-plot\r\n  - [ ] Make sure pom.xml contains the right entries\r\n  - [ ] Move the repository to github.com/scijava\r\n  - [ ] Update the travis configuration because groupId and artifactId changed, maybe reset the version\r\n  - [ ] Make the first release of scijava-plot\r\n- [ ] Rebase this PR to remove the WIP commit and change the dependency to the released version of scijava-plot\r\n- [ ] Merge this PR\r\n- [ ] Merge the PR in imagej-legacy\r\n"}

{"id":1091342203,"created_at":"2021-12-30T23:22:01Z","updated_at":"2022-01-17T22:35:53Z","state":"open","title":"Swing support: example file (its content) in the issue itself (via \"native-image\")","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/graal/issues/4165","body":"**Feature request**\r\n\r\nPlease include the following information:\r\n\r\n**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**\r\n\r\nThe below example, shown after a ---- line, can not be compiled via native-image.\r\n\r\nIt would be convenient if this would work out of the box for default/\"vanilla\" \r\nswing applications (at the least simple ones).\r\n\r\n**Describe the solution you'd like.**\r\n\r\nI would appreciate if some minimal swing support would be possible. There are\r\nother issues and blog posts where people were able to get at the least some \r\nswing applications to work, but these are a bit tedious to do (for instance, one\r\nrequired downloading some external program, so I'd prefer if I could just ask\r\nnative-image to download what it needs optionally, and proceed with it, rather\r\nthan have to collect what I need on my own, if possible).\r\n\r\nIf someone on the GraalVM team has time and motivation, perhaps it could be done\r\nto see so that at the least the basic functionality, buttons etc... may work via \r\nswing + native-image. People say that swing is outdated and deprecated \r\ncompared to JavaFX and that may be, but it would still be nice at the least\r\nfor simple applications to work.\r\n\r\n**Describe who do you think will benefit the most.**\r\n\r\nI believe the net benefit for the GraalVM users would be that they could get\r\nnative swing apps in one binary to work; which they could distribute (e. g.\r\nmy use case is to get some functionality into it, and have that be usable\r\nfor a few elderly people in my local area. I can work around it, that's ok,\r\ndefault java works just fine, but I'd love to be able to switch to GraalVM\r\ncompletely for everything related to java in the long run.).\r\n\r\n**Describe alternatives you've considered.**\r\n\r\nWell - I can use alternatives of course, which I am already doing, but I\r\nam not interested in the alternatives. {color: blue; font-size: 50px;}\");\r\n        styleSheet.addRule(\".someclass2 {color: green;}\");\r\n\r\n        htmlEditorKit.setStyleSheet(styleSheet);\r\n        htmlDocument = (HTMLDocument) htmlEditorKit.createDefaultDocument();\r\n        JTextPane jTextPane = new JTextPane();\r\n        jTextPane.setEditorKit(htmlEditorKit);\r\n        jTextPane.setDocument(htmlDocument);\r\n\r\n {"id":1216593187,"created_at":"2022-04-26T23:27:06Z","updated_at":"2022-04-26T23:27:06Z","state":"open","title":"Fix/image format is null export image or elevations example","html_url":"https://github.com/NASAWorldWind/WorldWindJava/pull/245","body":"**Note:** Filling out this template is required. Any pull request that does not include enough information to be reviewed in a timely manner may be closed at the\r\nmaintainer's discretion.\r\n\r\n### Description of the Change\r\n\r\n- Fixed bug where the format chosen for exporting images was always returning null, preventing the user from exporting any images except for elevations.\r\n- Added more file filters to the Swing FileChooser and added a hashmap for matching those extensions to mime types\r\n\r\n### Why Should This Be In Core?\r\n\r\nGiving new developers and users an example of how to export georeferenced images from WWD will greatly help their efforts in creating specialized versions of WWD, or how to add this functionality to their current WWD products.\r\n\r\n### Benefits\r\n\r\nDevelopers will be able to build off of this example and produce locally saved imagery. \r\n\r\n### Potential Drawbacks\r\n\r\nIf any of the WMS endpoints end up not supporting the mimetypes I added (like how arcGIS supports image/tiff but not image/tif) then those extensions would have to be removed from the added user options.\r\n\r\n### Applicable Issues\r\n\r\nIt would be great though if there was another example of how to make these export functions used the locally cached map tiles instead of requesting them repeatedly from a WMS endpoint.  I know the elevations are exported by reading local data, but for some reason the Image capture functions don't seem to be able to read / access / or modify a local cache and instead it defaults to making new WMS requests."}
{"id":1167623084,"created_at":"2022-03-13T16:09:54Z","updated_at":"2022-03-13T16:20:34Z","state":"open","title":"Aqui la solucion a tu problema","html_url":"https://github.com/Erik1935/Reloj/issues/1","body":"\r\nimport java.awt.Color;\r\nimport java.awt.GradientPaint;\r\nimport java.awt.Graphics2D;\r\nimport java.io.IOException;\r\nimport javax.imageio.ImageIO;\r\nimport javax.swing.JFrame;\r\nimport javax.swing.JPanel;\r\nimport java.awt.image.BufferedImage;\r\nimport java.awt.Graphics;\r\nimport java.awt.Paint;\r\nimport java.awt.event.ActionEvent;\r\nimport javax.swing.Timer;\r\n\r\npublic class Main extends JPanel {\r\n\r\n    private Timer tick;\r\n    private int dx = 0;\r\n    private int x = 0;\r\n    private int y = 0;\r\n    private final BufferedImage manecilla;\r\n\r\n    public Main() {\r\n        setFocusable(true);\r\n        manecilla = cargarImg(\"/manecilla.png\");\r\n        tick = new Timer(1000, null);\r\n        tick.addActionListener(this::tickManecilla);\r\n        tick.setRepeats(true);\r\n        tick.start();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public int getX() {\r\n        return x;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public void setX(int x) {\r\n        this.x = x;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public int getY() {\r\n        return y;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public void setY(int y) {\r\n        this.y = y;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    @Override\r\n    public void paintComponent(Graphics g) {\r\n        Graphics2D d2 = (Graphics2D) g.create(); //Creamos el objeto Graphics2D\r\n        Paint gradientBackground = new GradientPaint(0, 0, Color.BLACK, 0, getHeight(), Color.lightGray);\r\n        d2.setPaint(gradientBackground);\r\n        d2.fillRect(0, 0, getWidth(), getHeight());  //Actualizamos el fondo del panel.\r\n        d2.translate(getWidth() / 2, getHeight() / 2);//Lo trasladamos en medio del panel\r\n        d2.scale(1, 1);//Escalamos el objeto\r\n        d2.rotate(Math.toRadians(getX()), manecilla.getWidth() / 2, manecilla.getHeight() / 2);//Rotamos\r\n        d2.drawImage(manecilla, 0, 0, this);//Dibujamos la imagen\r\n        d2.dispose();//Liberamos el objeto d2 para la memoria\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    BufferedImage cargarImg(String name) {\r\n        try {\r\n            return ImageIO.read(Main.class.getResourceAsStream(name));\r\n        } catch (IOException ex) {\r\n            System.out.println(ex);\r\n        }\r\n        return null;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        JFrame f = new JFrame();\r\n        f.add(new Main());\r\n        f.setVisible(true);\r\n        f.setSize(400, 400);\r\n        f.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    /**\r\n     * Tu misma logica aplicada pero en un ActionEvent\r\n     *\r\n     * @param e\r\n     */\r\n    private void tickManecilla(ActionEvent e) {\r\n        dx += 10;\r\n        if (dx == 360) {\r\n            dx = 0;\r\n        }\r\n        setX(dx);\r\n        repaint();\r\n    }\r\n    /**\r\n     * Usar hilos con swing ocasiona errores y tienes un mal manejo de fps\r\n     * tienes 2 opciones o usas la logica de nucleo de un loop como el de un\r\n     * juego\r\n     * para controlar la velocidad de la animacion\r\n     * <p>\r\n     * O usas un swing.Timer para tener mas control con los ticks en internet\r\n     * hay muchos\r\n     * ejemplos sobre eso\r\n     */"}
